[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2017-north-lanarkshire-council-election] The election saw the Scottish National Party overtake Labour as the largest party on the council.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2017-north-lanarkshire-council-election] Despite the SNP winning the most seats and most votes, North Lanarkshire was run by a Labour administration supported by the Scottish Conservatives.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2017-north-lanarkshire-council-election] Labour leader Jim Logue was appointed Leader of the Council with the support of Conservative and Independent councillors.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2017-north-lanarkshire-council-election] + = Sitting Councillor for Cumbernauld South Ward.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] An election for the Scottish Parliament was held on 7 May 2026 to elect all 129 members of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] It was the seventh general election since the devolved parliament was established in 1999.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The governing Scottish National Party (SNP) secured a fifth consecutive term as they emerged as the largest party, despite losing six seats and falling seven short of a majority.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In the previous election, held five years prior, Nicola Sturgeon led the SNP to a fourth term in government, falling only a seat short of a majority.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The party later entered a power-sharing agreement with the Scottish Greens.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sturgeon resigned in 2023 and was succeeded by Humza Yousaf.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Yousaf ended the agreement with the Greens and later resigned after the Greens tabled a motion of no confidence vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Swinney succeeded him amid party turmoil in the SNP.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In the 2024 UK general election, Scottish Labour won a landslide and made a resurgence of support - its best result since 2010 in Scotland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Polls in the run-up to the election campaign suggested the SNP would emerge as the largest party for a fifth Holyrood election running, although focus weighed on who would emerge as the second largest, with the rise of Reform UK across the UK.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The SNP won the election with 58 MSPs, falling seven short of a majority.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Reform and Labour both won 17 seats, followed by the Greens on 15, the Conservatives on 12 and the Liberal Democrats on 10.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] It was the worst performance at a Scottish Parliament election for both Labour and Conservatives, with the former's seat share decreasing for the sixth consecutive election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Conversely, the Greens had their best-ever result, going into double figures for the first time and winning their first constituency seats.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Reform enjoyed a rise in support, although they were the only party not to win constituency seats.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The key issues dominating the election included the economy; income tax and the cost of living, healthcare, energy, housing and immigration - although the latter is a reserved issues, it remained a topic of debate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The SNP also argued the case for another referendum on Scottish independence.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] This was the first election contested using the new constituency boundaries implemented following the Second Periodic review.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The election was held on the same day as the local elections in England and the Senedd election in Wales, in which Plaid Cymru were victorious.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] With Sinn Féin also in government in Northern Ireland, this would mark the first time that all three devolved nations were governed by first ministers opposed to the United Kingdom.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Since the 2021 Scottish Parliament election, Scottish politics has undergone a period of significant leadership transitions and shifting governing arrangements.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In that election, the Scottish National Party (SNP) won 64 seats, falling one short of an overall majority.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] This led Nicola Sturgeon to negotiate the Bute House Agreement with the Scottish Greens, which brought Green MSPs into the government for the first time to secure a pro-independence majority in the chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sturgeon's final term as First Minister was marked by a renewed push for a second independence referendum, though this was checked by a UK Supreme Court ruling in 2022 stating Holyrood could not legislate for a vote without Westminster's consent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Her government also faced intense debate over the Gender Recognition Reform (Scotland) Bill, which was passed by the Scottish Parliament but was ultimately blocked by the UK government.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In February 2023, Sturgeon unexpectedly announced her resignation, citing the personal toll of the office and a desire to make way for new leadership.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Humza Yousaf won the subsequent turbulent leadership contest, becoming Scotland's first ethnic minority First Minister.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] His tenure was characterised by the ongoing Operation Branchform police investigation into SNP finances and a difficult economic climate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In April 2024, Yousaf unilaterally terminated the Bute House Agreement with the Greens.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] This move backfired when the Greens withdrew their support for his leadership, and facing an imminent vote of no confidence, Yousaf resigned after thirteen months in office.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] John Swinney, a former Deputy First Minister and the former SNP leader while the party was in opposition, was elected unopposed to succeed Yousaf and led a minority government into the elections.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] His leadership focused on party stabilisation following the 2024 UK general election, which saw Labour win a landslide victory and Scottish Labour replacing the SNP as the largest party in Scotland by Westminster seat count.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] However, the SNP later recovered in the polls amid the unpopularity of both Prime Minister Keir Starmer and Scottish Labour Leader Anas Sarwar, with Swinney leading his party into the 2026 elections and promising to deliver independence if re-elected.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] While the constitutional debate around independence stayed central to Scottish discourse during Swinney's premiership, the immediate path to a second referendum remained stalled by legal and political obstacles.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In May 2024, the Conservative prime minister Rishi Sunak called the 2024 United Kingdom general election to be held on 4 July, which was won by the Labour Party, with Keir Starmer succeeding Sunak as prime minister the following day.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Amid the national election, Scottish Conservative leader Douglas Ross announced his intention to resign as leader of the Scottish Conservatives upon the election of his successor.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Russell Findlay, who had been considered a frontrunner for the position, announced his candidacy for leader on 22 July.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Facing fellow MSPs Murdo Fraser and Meghan Gallacher, Findlay received 52% of MSP endorsements and was elected leader with 61.7% of the first-preference vote among party members.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 27 September he become leader of the largest opposition party in the Scottish Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] He formed his Shadow Cabinet on 8 October.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 9 February 2026, Scottish Labour leader Anas Sarwar held a press conference in Glasgow to publicly call for Prime Minister Keir Starmer to resign.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar stated that "the distraction needs to end and the leadership in Downing Street has to change," citing a series of "mistakes" that he believed were undermining Labour's prospects in the upcoming elections.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar described Starmer as "a decent man" and "a friend", but argued that his (that is, Sarwar's) primary loyalty was to Scotland and that the Prime Minister's continued leadership was sabotaging the party's future.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The primary catalyst for this intervention was the fallout from the appointment of Peter Mandelson as British Ambassador to the United States, which had come under intense scrutiny due to Mandelson's past ties to child sex offender Jeffrey Epstein.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar's move followed the resignations of Starmer’s chief of staff, Morgan McSweeney, and director of communications, Tim Allan.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar said he had spoken to Starmer earlier that day to inform him of his decision, stating that the two had "disagreed" on the necessity of his resignation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In the immediate aftermath, senior Cabinet members including Deputy Prime Minister David Lammy and Chancellor Rachel Reeves rallied behind Starmer, emphasising his mandate and urging party unity.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Within Scottish Labour, the move caused significant friction; while Monica Lennon supported Sarwar's "leadership", others such as former Scottish Secretary Ian Murray branded the call a threat to party stability.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] First Minister John Swinney and Scottish Conservative leader Russell Findlay characterised the situation as "opportunism" and a "meltdown".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Addressing the Parliamentary Labour Party later that evening, Starmer remained defiant, stating he had "won every fight I've ever been in" and refused to walk away.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In January 2026, the millionaire Easdale brothers "reportedly pledged a six-figure donation to Scottish Labour".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar said that they did not make any policy demands of Scottish Labour but that they want the SNP out of power.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In February 2026, the Alba Party entered a major financial and organisational crisis which ultimately led to the party being wound down ahead of the election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Party leader Kenny MacAskill warned members that Alba was unlikely to contest the election due to financial irregularities linked to alleged fraud and declining income, while discussions were ongoing with the Electoral Commission regarding compliance and the party’s future registration.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The announcement triggered internal divisions within the party, with several National Executive Committee members and candidates disputing the leadership’s handling of the situation and calling for a membership ballot on whether Alba should stand in the election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The dispute escalated publicly in late February and early March, amid reports of resignations, candidate withdrawals and disagreements over access to party membership data.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Party officials later stated that Alba was financially insolvent and unable to meet existing debts, while internal factions argued the party could continue if leadership changed and additional funds were raised.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 8 March 2026, MacAskill announced that Alba would be wound down due to its financial position, effectively ending the party founded by Alex Salmond in 2021 and confirming it would not participate in the election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Under the Scottish Elections (Reform) Act 2020, ordinary general elections to the Scottish Parliament are held on the first Thursday in May five years after the 2021 election, i.e. on 7 May 2026.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] This Act superseded the Scotland Act 1998, which had set elections in every fourth year.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] 42 MSPs did not seek re-election, which was a record.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Eight of those stepping down were first elected at the formation of the Scottish Parliament in 1999, but only five have had unbroken service.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Richard Lochhead briefly resigned his regional seat to contest a Moray by-election in 2006; Rhoda Grant lost her seat in 2003 and returned at the 2007 election; Sarah Boyack lost her seat in the 2016 election and returned in 2019.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Of the original MSPs from 1999 with unbroken service, only three contested the 2026 election: Jackie Baillie, Fergus Ewing and John Swinney.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 21 February 2026, Alba Party leader Kenny MacAskill announced that the party was unlikely to be able to stand candidates due to an internal financial crisis.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] After this announcement Tommy Sheridan, Angus MacNeil, Christina Hendry and Suzanne Blackley issued a joint statement in which they offered to take over leadership of the Alba Party to ensure it can contest the election but this ultimately never materialised.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 8 March 2026, MacAskill announced that the party would deregister and therefore would be unable to stand in the election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Your Party originally intended to stand candidates, but it was later reported that they would miss the deadline due to what Scottish representative Niall Christie called "inaction and decisions taken by Your Party at a UK level".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The total number of Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) elected to the Parliament is 129.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The Scottish Parliament uses an additional member system (AMS), designed to produce approximate proportional representation for each region.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] There are eight regions, each sub-divided into smaller constituencies.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Each constituency elects one MSP by the plurality (first past the post) system of election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Each region elects seven additional MSPs using an additional member system.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] A modified D'Hondt method, using the constituency results, is used to elect these additional MSPs.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The boundaries used for the Scottish Parliament elections were then revised for the 2011 election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The Boundary Commission also recommended changes to the electoral regions used to elect "list" members of the Scottish Parliament, which were also implemented in 2011.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The Second Periodic Review of constituency and regional boundaries began in September 2022 and was completed by May 2025.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The proposals were formally approved in October 2025, establishing the constituencies and regions to form the basis for the 2026 election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] According to Professor John Curtice, main campaign issues included the economy, cost of living, health and social care services and immigration.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Other issues include energy, housing and Scottish independence.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Another issue is Starmer's leadership after Sarwar called for him to resign.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 10 March 2026, BBC Scotland's podcast *Scotcast* started airing leader interviews with the party leaders in the run-up to the election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 19 March, Malcolm Offord and Nigel Farage launched Reform UK's manifesto in Bishopton, Renfrewshire, positioning itself as a challenger to the established parties with a platform centred on tax cuts, immigration control and economic deregulation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] A key proposal is to reduce Scottish income tax to levels below those in the rest of the UK, alongside broader commitments to cut public spending and roll back green policies in order to lower energy costs.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The party has also emphasised stricter law and order measures, opposition to what it describes as “net zero ideology”, and support for domestic energy production and business growth through reduced regulation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] They also unveiled their constituency candidates.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The following day, Stuart Niven, the candidate for Dundee City West, was suspended following revelations that he was disqualified as a company director.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] In the days that followed, four more candidates stood down from standing for Reform UK.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 21 March, the Scottish Greens announced a commitment to raising the minimum wage for care workers to £15 per hour.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Other policies announced by the party include, expanding funded childcare, higher tax on the super rich, big businesses, big banks, as well as casinos and bookies, and a commitment to free bus travel for everyone in Scotland via a bus network under public control.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The *Holyrood Sources* podcast announced that they would host a hustings event with the party leaders on 1 April.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 31 March, Guy Ingerson was replaced by Maggie Chapman as top candidate in North East Scotland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 1 April, Scottish Labour candidate for Glasgow Southside Mohammed Ameen was replaced by Rashid Hussain following criminal charges.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] SNP candidate and leader of the SNP group on North Lanarkshire Council, Tracy Carragher was suspended from the party and dropped as an election candidate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 4 April, the Scottish Greens announced a commitment to end all NHS dental charges, ensuring free dental care for all in Scotland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The party also stated that it would expand the role of dental therapists in order to speed up waiting times.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Russell Findlay launched the Scottish Conservatives manifesto in Edinburgh on 7 April with a strong emphasis on the cost of living, positioning the election as a choice between continued public spending under the SNP and lower-tax, “common sense” economic policies.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Key proposals included cutting income tax, supporting North Sea oil and gas development, and reducing what the party describes as wasteful government spending.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The party has also focused on improving public services such as healthcare and education, alongside a broader agenda centred on economic growth, law and order, and opposition to further tax rises.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 12 April, UK Health Secretary Wes Streeting stated on LBC that the UK Government would never grant the Scottish Parliament the powers to hold a second independence referendum.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] These comments were criticised by the SNP and Scottish Greens.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] LBC journalist Gina Davidson stated that Streeting’s comments might have just made the election catch fire and result in SNP supporters to go and turnout to vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The subject was brought up in the leader’s debate hosted in Paisley that evening where Anas Sarwar was challenged and refused to answer on what mechanism would need to be in place for a second referendum to be granted.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Scottish Labour leader Anas Sarwar launched his party’s manifesto in Edinburgh on 13 April, presenting the election as an opportunity to “fix” public services after nearly two decades of SNP government, appealing to the public to give him “five years to fix the SNP’s mess”.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The manifesto outlined a programme focused on economic reform and public service investment, including plans to build over 50,000 affordable homes, recruit additional teachers, and reduce business rates.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] It also proposed tax changes aimed at easing pressure on middle-income earners, reforms to public bodies, and support for sectors such as the arts, alongside a more centrist economic approach that includes openness to new nuclear energy projects.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 14 April, the internal pro-LGBT group Scottish Labour Against Bigotry attacked the manifesto as "explicitly transphobic" due to its stated commitment to "single-[biological] sex spaces, in NHS wards, schools, sport and everyday life", and urged the electorate not to vote for the party.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 14 April, the Scottish Greens launched their manifesto in Glasgow, presenting promises such as taking bus services into public ownership, introducing a universal basic income, and widening access to funded childcare.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The SNP launched their manifesto on 16 April in Glasgow with key pledges including capping the price of essential food items, introducing a £2 nationwide bus fare cap, and supporting business through a new “major projects office” and high-growth unit.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The party has committed to no income tax increases for most earners while proposing targeted taxes on large corporations, alongside increased investment in healthcare and education.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Additional policies include banning smartphones in classrooms and a £10,000 deposit support scheme for first-time buyers, with Scottish independence remaining a central objective.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The Liberal Democrats launched their manifesto on 17 April.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Claims and speculation surrounding a potential alliance between Scottish Labour and Reform UK became a significant point of contention during the campaign period, particularly in exchanges between party leaders and during televised debates.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] During the SNP’s campaign launch on 26 March, First Minister John Swinney argued that the absence of an SNP majority could lead to what he described as a “grubby deal” between Anas Sarwar and Reform UK.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Swinney framed the prospect as a risk of Labour seeking power through informal arrangements with parties on the right, positioning the SNP as the only safeguard against such an outcome, citing issues within Fife Council as a recent example.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar rejected the claim, stating that Scottish Labour would not enter into any agreements or cooperation with Reform UK, and reiterated that his party’s focus was on winning a mandate to govern in its own right.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Senior Labour figures indicated that gains in key central belt constituencies, combined with vote splitting among unionist parties, could potentially allow the party to form a minority government.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] However, polling experts, including Professor John Curtice and academic Mark McGeoghegan, expressed strong scepticism, noting that Labour remained significantly behind the SNP in most polls and that the rise of Reform UK was more likely to divide the anti-SNP vote than to assist Labour.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Analysts described the scenario as highly unlikely without a substantial and unprecedented shift in voter support.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Scottish Conservative leader Russell Findlay refused to rule out that his party would vote to make Sarwar the First Minister in this scenario.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] During the Channel 4 News leaders' debate on 14 April, Malcolm Offord claimed that Anas Sarwar had suggested cooperation between Scottish Labour and Reform UK to prevent the SNP from remaining in power.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Offord alleged that the conversation took place following the recording of *Question Time* at Paisley Town Hall in December 2025.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar rejected the claim following the debate, describing it as untrue and reiterating that Scottish Labour would not enter into any deals or arrangements with Reform UK.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The dispute continued after the broadcast, with Offord standing by his remarks in subsequent media appearances, while Sarwar described the allegation as a "desperate lie" and repeated that there would be no deals or "backroom stitch-ups".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] The row was amplified by other parties during the campaign, with the SNP citing the exchange as evidence of a potential post-election alignment, while Labour and other parties dismissed the claims as speculative and politically motivated.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Reform UK councillor and candidate Thomas Kerr stated that Sarwar had made similar remarks to him in November 2025, claiming that Labour MP Maureen Burke was present during the exchange, while Offord said an aide had also witnessed his alleged conversation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Reform sources further suggested comparable discussions had taken place in Holyrood in recent months.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] On 20 April, the dispute widened further following additional claims and counterclaims involving Graham Simpson and Kerr.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar alleged that Simpson had privately criticised senior Reform figures, claims which Simpson rejected as “completely ridiculous”.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Simpson in turn asserted that Sarwar had approached him on three occasions in Holyrood to discuss working together to remove the SNP from power, echoing similar claims made by Offord and Kerr in the preceding days.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p01] Sarwar denied these allegations, maintaining that no such discussions had taken place.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] The SNP won a fifth successive Scottish Parliament election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Labour and Reform tied for second place.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] The Scottish Greens won elected their first constituency MSPs and also elected the first transgender members to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] A number of high profile MSPs were unseated including Angus Robertson, Jackson Carlaw, Kaukab Stewart, Fergus Ewing, Ash Regan and Monica Lennon.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Following the election, Jackie Baillie and John Swinney were the only remaining MSPs who had served in the parliament continuously since the 1999 election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Kenny Gibson and Pauline McNeill, who were also first elected in 1999, had each been absent for one parliamentary session.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] John Swinney had the opportunity to form a new government, and was subsequently re-elected as First Minister by the Scottish Parliament on 20 May 2026.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] He named a new cabinet, the second Swinney government, continuing to lead a minority government.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Reform UK's leader Malcolm Offord lost out in Inverclyde but was elected on the party list.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] John Swinney ruled out holding any talks with the party.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Despite the poor result for his party, Anas Sarwar told reporters that he would remain the leader of Scottish Labour.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] On 12 June 2026, the French government agency Viginum reported that an Israeli private influence firm was involved in election interference, including targeting John Swinney.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/2026-scottish-parliament-election-p02] Following the election, YouGov published a demographic breakdown of the election results.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] An **act of parliament**, as a form of primary legislation, is a text of law passed by the legislative body of a jurisdiction (often a parliament or council).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In most countries with a parliamentary system of government, acts of parliament begin as a bill, which the legislature votes on.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Depending on the structure of government, this text may then be subject to assent or approval from the executive branch.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] A draft act of parliament is known as a bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In other words, a bill is a proposed law that needs to be discussed in the parliament before it can become a law.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In territories with a Westminster system, most bills that have any possibility of becoming law are introduced into parliament by the government.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] This will usually happen following the publication of a "white paper", setting out the issues and the way in which the proposed new law is intended to deal with them.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] A bill may also be introduced into parliament without formal government backing; this is known as a private member's bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In territories with a multicameral parliament, most bills may be first introduced in any chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] However, certain types of legislation are required, either by constitutional convention or by law, to be introduced into a specific chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] For example, bills imposing a tax, or involving public expenditure, are introduced into the House of Commons in the United Kingdom, Canada's House of Commons, Lok Sabha of India and Ireland's Dáil as a matter of law.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Conversely, bills proposed by the Law Commission and consolidation bills traditionally start in the House of Lords.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Once introduced, a bill must go through a number of stages before it can become law.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In theory, this allows the bill's provisions to be debated in detail, and for amendments to the original bill to also be introduced, debated, and agreed to.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In bicameral parliaments, a bill that has been approved by the chamber into which it was introduced then sends the bill to the other chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Broadly speaking, each chamber must separately agree to the same version of the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Finally, the approved bill receives assent; in most territories this is merely a formality and is often a function exercised by the head of state.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In some countries, such as in France, Belgium, Luxembourg, Spain and Portugal, the term for a bill differs depending on whether it is initiated by the government (when it is known as a "draft"), or by the parliament (a "proposition", i.e., a private member's bill).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading: As in the UK, the stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Again, the second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] A defeat for a government bill on this reading signifies a major loss.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Consideration in detail: This usually takes place on the floor of the House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Generally, committees sit on the floor of the House and consider the bill in detail.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Very rarely do debates occur during this stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Representatives; to the House of Representatives, if it is a Senate bill), which may amend it.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are posted back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The State of Queensland's Parliament is unicameral and skips this and the rest of the stages.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Representatives amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu, or reject them.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] However, the Senate may not amend money bills, though it can "request" the House to make amendments.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] A bill may pass backward and forward several times at this stage, as each House amends or rejects changes proposed by the other.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If each House insists on disagreeing with the other, the bill is lost.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: Often, when a bill cannot be passed in the same form by both Houses, it is "laid aside", i.e. abandoned.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the federal Parliament, there is also a special constitutional procedure allowing the passage of the bill without the separate agreement of both houses.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the House twice passes the same bill, and the Senate twice fails to pass that bill (either through rejection or through the passage of unacceptable amendments), then the Governor-General may dissolve both Houses of Parliament simultaneously and call an election for the entire Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] After the election, if the House again passes the bill, but the deadlock between the Houses persists, then the Governor-General may convene a joint sitting of both Houses, where a final decision will be taken on the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Although the House and the Senate sit as a single body, bills passed at a joint sitting are treated as if they had been passed by each chamber separately.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The procedure only applies if the bill originated in the House of Representatives.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Six double dissolutions have occurred, though a joint sitting was only held once, in 1974.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The bill is sent to the viceroy (the Governor-General for the Commonwealth; the governor for a state; the administrator for a territory) for royal assent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Acts in the Australian Capital Territory do not require this step.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading: This stage involves a debate on the general principles of the bill and is followed by a vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The second reading of a government bill is usually approved.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the bill is read a second time, then it progresses to the committee stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a standing committee of the Commons or Senate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Report stage: this takes place on the floor of the appropriate chamber, and allows the House or Senate to approve amendments made in committee, or to propose new ones.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Senate, if it originated in the House of Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Senate bill), where it will face a virtually identical process.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the other House amends the bill, the bill and amendments are sent back to the original House for a further stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Senate/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] It may agree to them, amend them, propose other amendments in lieu or reject them.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Disagreement between the Houses: There is no specific procedure to resolve a dispute between the houses.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Either house can amend or reject a bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The debate on each stage is actually debate on a specific motion.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] For the first reading, there is no debate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the Report stage, the debate is on the motions for specific amendments.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Once a bill has passed both Houses in an identical form, it is presented to the Governor General, who gives it royal assent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Although the Governor General can refuse to assent a bill, this power has never been exercised.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Bills being reviewed by Parliament are assigned numbers: 2 to 200 for government bills, 201 to 1000 for private member's bills, and 1001 up for private bills.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] They are preceded by C- if they originate in the House of Commons, or S- if they originate in the Senate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] For example, Bill C-250 was a private member's bill introduced in the House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Bills C-1 and S-1 are pro forma bills, and are introduced at the beginning of each session in order to assert the right of each Chamber to manage its own affairs.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] They are introduced and read a first time, and then are dropped from the Order Paper.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading – discussion stage: This stage consists of detailed consideration of the bill and proposed amendments.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third reading – voting stage: This stage is confined only to arguments either in support of the bill or for its rejection as a whole, without referring to its details.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] After the bill is passed, it is sent to the other house.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Bill in the other house (Rajya Sabha): After a bill, other than a money bill, is transmitted to the other house, it goes through all the stages in that house as that in the first house.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] But if the bill passed by one house is amended by the other house, it goes back to the originating house.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] President's approval: When a bill is passed by both the houses, it is sent to the President for his approval.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The President can assent or withhold his assent to a bill or he can return a bill, other than a money bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the President gives his assent, the bill is published in *The Gazette of India* and becomes an Act from the date of his assent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If he withholds his assent, the bill is dropped, which is known as pocket veto.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The pocket veto is not written in the constitution and has only been exercised once, by President Zail Singh in 1986, over the postal act where the government wanted to open postal letters without warrant.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the president returns it for reconsideration, the Parliament must do so, but if it is passed again and returned to him, he must give his assent to it.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the Irish Parliament, the Oireachtas, bills pass through the following stages.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Bills may be initiated in either the Dáil or the Seanad, and must pass both houses.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second stage – this involves a discussion of the general principle of the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] It is introduced by the sponsoring minister (or in the case of a private member's bill, by the member) and is followed by contributions from the floor of the house.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Finally, the debate is brought to a conclusion by voting on the proposal "that the bill now be read a second time".
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third stage, commonly referred to as the Committee Stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] This involves section by section scrutiny of the bill and any amendments which have been tabled.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the Dáil this usually takes place in a committee room and will involve examination by one of the select committees.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the Seanad, this stage takes place in the chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The Seanad may only make recommendations rather than amendments, in the case of a money bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Fourth stage, commonly referred to as the Report Stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] At this point, a version of the bill incorporating any changes made at the Committee Stage is printed for consideration.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In both houses, this stage is taken on the floor of the chamber.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Amendments may be considered at this stage but must arise from matters discussed or changes made at the Committee Stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Fifth stage: in practice this is a formality, taken with the fourth stage and referred to as the Report and Final Stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Passage in the other house: the same stages are repeated in the other house and the bill is then deemed to have been passed, except that any bill initiated in the Dáil and amended by the Seanad must return to the Dáil for final consideration.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Signature: once the bill has passed both houses it is sent to the President for signature.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The signed copy is then enrolled in the Office of the Supreme Court.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Select committee stage: The bill is considered by a select committee, which scrutinises the bill in detail and hears public submissions on the matter.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The select committee may recommend amendments to the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading: The general principles of the bill are debated, and a vote is held.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is put before a Committee of the House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Committee of the House: The bill is debated and voted on, clause by clause, by the whole House sitting as a committee.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third reading: Summarising arguments are made, and a final vote is taken.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the bill is approved, it is passed to the Governor-General for royal assent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] New Zealand has no upper house, and so no further approval is necessary.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] A draft piece of legislation is called a *bill*; when this is passed by Parliament it becomes an *act* and part of statute law.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] There are two types of bill and act, *public* and *private*.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Public acts apply to the whole of the UK or a number of its constituent countries – England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Private acts are local and personal in their effect, giving special powers to bodies such as local authorities or making exceptions to the law in particular geographic areas.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] First reading: This is a formality; no vote occurs.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The bill is presented and ordered to be printed and, in the case of private members' bills, a date is set for second reading.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading: A debate on the general principles of the bill is followed by a vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Committee stage: This usually takes place in a public bill committee in the Commons and on the floor of the House in the Lords.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The committee considers each clause of the bill, and may make amendments to it.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Consideration (or report) stage: This takes place on the floor of the House, and is a further opportunity to amend the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Unlike committee stage, the House need not consider every clause of the bill, only those to which amendments have been tabled.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third reading: A debate on the final text of the bill, as amended in the House of Lords.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Further amendments may be tabled at this stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Passage: The bill is then sent to the other House (to the Lords, if it originated in the Commons; to the Commons, if it is a Lords bill), which may amend it.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Consideration of Lords/Commons amendments: The House in which the bill originated considers the amendments made in the other House.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: the bill is passed with any amendments and becomes an act of Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Stage one: The bill is considered by one or more of the subject committees of the parliament, which normally take evidence from the bill's promoter and other interested parties before reporting to the parliament on the principles of the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Other committees, notably the Finance and Subordinate Legislation Committees, may also feed in at this stage.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The report from the committee is followed by a debate in the full parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Stage two: The bill returns to the subject committee where it is subject to line-by-line scrutiny and amendment.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] This is similar to the committee stage in the UK Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Stage three: The bill as amended by the committee returns to the full parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] There is a further opportunity for amendment, followed by a debate on the whole bill, at the end of which the parliament decides whether to pass the bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Royal assent: After the bill has been passed, the presiding officer submits it to the monarch for royal assent.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] However, he cannot do so until a four-week period has elapsed during which the law officers of the Scottish government or the UK government can refer the bill to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom for a ruling on whether it is within the powers of the parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] There are special procedures for emergency bills, member's bills (similar to private member's bills in the UK Parliament), committee bills, and private bills.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In Singapore, the bill passes through these certain stages before becoming into an Act of Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Second reading: In this stage, the bill is further discussed and put to a second vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If more than half of the votes are ayes the bill proceeds to the select committee.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Select committee: The select committee consists of people not only from the parliaments, but also the people who could be affected by the bill is passed into law.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] This is to ensure equality and that the bill is fair for all.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If the bill is in favour, it will proceed to the third reading.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Third reading: After the select committee has discussed and are in favour of the bill, they will put it to a vote.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] At this juncture, if the votes are more than half ayes, it will be sent to the President of Singapore.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] President Assent: The president must give permission in order for the bill to be passed.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] If they approve it, it will become a statute passed down by the members of parliament which is called an Act of Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Acts passed by the Parliament of England did not originally have titles, and could only be formally cited by reference to the parliamentary session in which they were passed, with each individual act being identified by year and chapter number.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Descriptive titles began to be added to the enrolled acts by the official clerks, as a reference aid; over time, titles came to be included within the text of each bill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Since the mid-nineteenth century, it has also become common practice for acts to have a short title, as a convenient alternative to the sometimes lengthy main titles.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The Short Titles Act 1892, and its replacement the Short Titles Act 1896, gave short titles to many acts which previously lacked them.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The numerical citation of acts has also changed over time.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The original method was based on the regnal year (or years) in which the relevant parliamentary session met.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] This has been replaced in most territories by simple reference to the calendar year, with the first act passed being chapter 1, and so on.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] In the United Kingdom, legislation has referenced by year and chapter number since 1963 (Acts of Parliament Numbering and Citation Act 1962).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Each act is numbered consecutively based on the date it received royal assent, for example the 43rd act passed in 1980 would be 1980 chapter 43.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] The full reference includes the (short) title and would be the Magistrate's Court Act 1980 (c.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/act-of-parliament] Until the 1980s, acts of the Australian state of Victoria were numbered in a continuous sequence from 1857; thus the Age of Majority Act 1977 was No.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie developed as a market town in the late 17th century following the passing of an act of Parliament, the Airdrie Fairs and Market Act 1695 (c.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] 94 (S)) allowing it to hold a weekly market.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] It later grew in prominence as a centre for weaving and manufacturing, as well as being the settlement near several coalmines.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the mid 19th century, the town expanded greatly as a result of immigration and the development of iron works and railway links.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The first public library in Scotland was established in Airdrie in 1853.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] During the 20th century, industrial decline took place in Airdrie, with heavy industry closing down across much of the town.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the 21st century, Airdrie has continued as a regional centre for services and retail, as well as being a commuter settlement within the Central Belt.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Historically part of Lanarkshire, Airdrie forms a conurbation with its neighbour Coatbridge, in what was formerly the Monklands district, with a population of approximately 90,000.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie's name first appeared in the Register of the Great Seal of Scotland (Latin: *Registrum Magni Sigilii Regum Scotorum*) in 1373 as 'Ardre'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] By 1546 it had become 'Ardry' and by 1587 it was known as 'Ardrie'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 1630 it finally appeared in the Register as 'Airdrie'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Given the topography of the area, the most likely interpretation is that the name derives from the Gaelic *An Àrd Ruigh* meaning 'a level height' or 'high pasture land'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Another possibility is from the Gaelic *An Àrd Àirighe* meaning 'a sheiling, a summer pasture/shepherd's hut'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] A third possibility is the Gaelic *Ard Reidh* meaning 'a high plain'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] A less likely, non-Gaelic alternative, is the Brythonic, i.e.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Cumbric or North Welsh, *ard tref* (becoming ardre by process of assimilation), meaning 'a high steading or farmstead', which would date back to the times of the Kingdom of Strathclyde, before the expansion of Gaelic or English speech into the region.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airthrey Castle in Stirlingshire may have a similar derivation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] There is no evidence to support the claim (George Chalmers, Caledonia) that Airdrie is the site of the ancient battle of Arderyth.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Under the patronage of King Malcolm IV of Scotland Cistercian monks established an abbey at Melrose in 1136.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Five years later a daughter house was founded at Newbattle Abbey in Lothian.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 1160, Malcolm granted lands in central Scotland to the monks of Newbattle.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] These became known as the "Munklands" (Register of the Great Seal 1323).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Malcolm's Charter constitutes the oldest documentary record of place-names in the Monklands.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] *Dunduffes* has become directly translated into the modern Black Hill which, as the Charter states, lies at the eastern extremity of the parish.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The Charter does not mention anything resembling Airdrie, although this is where Airdrie is located.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie owes its existence to its location on the 'Hogs Back' – a ridge of land running from east to west.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] One very important aspect of the town's history was the Cistercian monks of Newbattle Abbey, which is why the area is called the Monklands.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The monks were farmers and some of their place names survive, e.g., Ryefield and Whifflet (the wheat flats).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Much of the land they used is known today as 'The Four Isles' (a housing estate named after four Scottish islands): Mull, Islay, Iona and Luing in the Petersburn area of modern Airdrie.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The monks of Newbattle had numerous establishments throughout the area including a farm grange at Drumpellier, Coatbridge, a court house at Kipps, a chapel in the area of Chapelhall and a number of corn mills.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The monks were also expert in the construction of roads.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the 12th century, they established the original Glasgow to Edinburgh road via Airdrie and Bathgate, to link up with their lands in Newbattle in East Lothian.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Definitive evidence of the existence of Airdrie as a tenantry was only made clear in 1503.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The old monks' road was via Cliftonhill (an area now in neighbouring Coatbridge), Airdrie House (now the site of Monklands Hospital), Aitchison Street, High Street, Hallcraig Street, Flowerhill Street and Colliertree Road.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The first houses in Airdrie were built along this road.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Development was slow and it was only around 1650 that evidence of the number of inhabitants was known at around 500 for the Airdrie area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] A large contingent of Airdrieonians fought at the Battle of Bothwell Brig during the Covenanter Rebellion of 1679; their banner can still be viewed at the local library.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] A significant event in Airdrie's history was the 1695 passing of a special act of Parliament, the **Airdrie Fairs and Market Act 1695** (c.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] 94 (S)) in the Scottish Parliament allowing Robert Hamilton of Airdrie to hold four fairs yearly and a weekly market in the town of 'Airdry'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This helped develop Airdrie from a 'farm town' into a thriving 'market town'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] However, Airdrie really came to prominence through its weaving industry.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie Weavers Society was founded in 1781 and flax was being grown in sixteen farms in and around the burgh.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the last decade of the eighteenth century, coal mining was in progress and around thirty colliers were employed.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Weaving continued to flourish making up a substantial part of the population of over 2,500 around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Given its large number of weavers, its geographic location and a large number of unemployed soldiers following the end of the Napoleonic Wars, Airdrie became a major centre of support for the Radical War of 1820.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The rapid pace of population growth continued and by 1821 there were 4,862 inhabitants.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] At this time, the number of houses being built increased dramatically and in 1821, by a local act of Parliament, the **Airdrie Improvement Act 1821** (1 & 2 Geo.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] 4. c. lx), Airdrie became a free and independent burgh of barony.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 1821, the first election of a town council took place and by August it had appointed an assessor, procurator fiscal, master of police and a town crier.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Anyone who had paid their 3 guineas was allowed to vote; there is even a record of a John Mackay voting despite being under 10 years old.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 1824, it was decided to build the Airdrie Town House, originally designed by Alexander Baird and now a local landmark known as the 'town clock'.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 1832, the Town House was used as a hospital due to the cholera outbreak of this year.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The enormous growth in population was not due to high birthrate, but instead due to an influx of residents from the Highlands and predominantly Ireland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This followed the Highland potato famine of the mid-1840s and also reflected the change from cottage industry to heavy industry in the area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Most of the Irish immigrant population were involved with mining and labouring.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This led to an increase in ironwork foundries around the area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Because of this explosion in industry, railway links were established starting in 1826.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] By 1862, the Airdrie and Bathgate Junction Railway provided a direct link to Edinburgh with Airdrie South Station providing the starting point for trains to Glasgow.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In August the Public Libraries Act (Scotland) 1853 was passed, and in November Airdrie Public Library became the first in Scotland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The dramatic rise in population and industry prompted the need for more accessible water supplies.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Until the mid-1800s, various wells were put in place feeding from surrounding streams in the area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] These served to provide many houses with private wells.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] By 1846 Airdrie and Coatbridge Water Company was founded to construct (along with Forth and Clyde Canal Company) the reservoir at Roughrigg.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Journalism in Airdrie began with "The Airdrie Literary Album" in 1828.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Several local newspapers began appearing around this time notably the Airdrie & Coatbridge Advertiser in 1855, which is still the most popular local paper today.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The prison was legalised in 1859 and had 51 cells.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie Working Men's Club was established in 1869.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Also around this time, football and cricket began to emerge as popular sports.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Following the codification of association football rules a local team called Excelsior was formed in 1878 which would later be renamed Airdrieonians.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Horse race meetings were also held in the town (1851–1870) but this land became the golf course for the newly formed Airdrie Golf Club in 1877.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Education posed a major problem with severe overcrowding in the few schools available, therefore three new school boards were established.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the early 1830s there were about 800 pupils while the town had about 7,000 residents.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Fees were routinely charged within the schools with the belief they should be self-supporting until an act of Parliament of 1889 relieved some of the infant classes in schools of this burden.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie Academy was built in 1849 and by 1919 all school boards were dissolved and Lanarkshire Education Authority took over responsibility for education throughout Lanarkshire.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] By the turn of the 20th century variety shows were becoming popular in the area and by 1911 the Pavilion in Graham Street was built which after initially being used as a music hall started showing cinematographic pictures.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Unfortunately it was destroyed by fire in 1917 but was rebuilt in 1919 and finally closed in 1970.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The New Cinema was opened in 1920 in Broomknoll Street but it too has since closed.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The town had no suitable venue for larger functions so in 1912 the Sir John Wilson Town Hall was opened (following an offer of £10,000 from Sir John Wilson).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] On 9 July 1918 nineteen miners died in the Stanrigg Pit Disaster.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The pit was situated in boggy land and collapsed after being saturated by heavy rainfall.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] At the end of the First World War, Airdrie was hard hit with many casualties from the war.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Unemployment reached 30% in the local area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] After years of moving from one site to another, the first purpose built library in Airdrie was opened in Anderson Street in 1895.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] However, this only lasted 30 years until the current Airdrie Library building was erected in 1925.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Conditions in the town did not really improve until well after the Second World War but in 1949 the Boots pharmaceutical company and Banner Textiles Ltd were attracted to the town (between them employing 1200).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] With this impetus, new companies began to consider Airdrie as a viable option for business and in 1958 Pye opened employing over 1000 people.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The emergence of industrial estates was also prevalent around this time (Newhouse, Chapelhall, and Brownsburn).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The Airdrie Arts Centre opened in 1967 in the former Airdrie Library building, and was a popular venue for concerts and plays, but was closed in 2012 by North Lanarkshire Council.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Between 1964 and 1991, the town was the location of a Royal Observer Corps monitoring bunker, to be used in the event of a nuclear attack.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The 1970s saw the opening of Monklands Hospital, which replaced an older hospital on the Airdrie House estate.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie hosted the National Mòd in 1993.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In the 21st century, the town has continued to grow as a residential settlement, with development and conversion of some town centre buildings, such as the Historic Orrs Department Store into new homes.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 2024, permission was given for a significant expansion of the town, with the creation of up to 3,000 new homes in East Airdrie on former mining land.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie is represented by several tiers of elected government.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] North Lanarkshire Council, the unitary local authority for Airdrie, is based at Motherwell, and is the executive, deliberative and legislative body responsible for local governance.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The Scottish Parliament is responsible for devolved matters such as education, health and justice, while reserved matters are dealt with by the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The town forms part of the burgh constituency of Airdrie and Shotts, electing one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 2005, changes to the constituency boundaries saw part of its area transferred to Motherwell and Wishaw, offset by the addition of part of Hamilton North and Bellshill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The current MP for the constituency since 2024 is the Scottish National Party's Kenneth Stevenson. who was preceded by Anum Qaisar from 2021 to 2024. .
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] For the purposes of the Scottish Parliament, Airdrie forms part of the Airdrie constituency.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This has slightly different boundaries from those of the UK Parliament constituency: previously the two seats were both titled "Airdrie and Shotts", however the Scottish Parliament seat was renamed to simply "Airdrie" ahead of the 2026 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The current Member of the Scottish Parliament (MSP) for Airdrie is Neil Grey MSP (Scottish National Party), who won this seat (then called Airdrie and Shotts) in 2021.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In addition to this, Airdrie is represented by seven regional MSPs from the Central Scotland and Lothians West.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Before Brexit, it was part of the Scotland European Parliament constituency.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Up until 1975, Airdrie had its own Burgh Council.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Between 1975 and 1996, Airdrie came under Monklands District Council operating in conjunction with Strathclyde Regional Council.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Monklands District Council was headquartered in the Coatbridge Municipal Building.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Many Airdrieonians felt short-changed by MDC's actions and a significant political scandal known as Monklandsgate greatly tarnished the council's reputation.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] After 1996, it came under the authority of the unitary North Lanarkshire Council.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] North Lanarkshire has many councillors; currently, the council is in control of the Labour group and the leader of the council is Jim Logue, councillor for Airdrie Central.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Chapelhall, Calderbank, Caldercruix, Gartness, Glenmavis, Greengairs, Longriggend, Plains, Stand, Upperton, Newhouse and Wattston are generally considered satellite villages of Airdrie.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Historical records of Airdrie's population are available from the 18th, the early decades of the 19th century, and into the early 20th century.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] As outlined in the history section, Airdrie's traditional economic activities of weaving, coal mining, and heavy industry have ceased to exist.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Although the Glenflagler Distillery is now closed, the town still retains a strong involvement in the whisky industry.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie was also home to a Crimpy Crisps factory.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Given its location near to Glasgow and other commercial or industrial areas, Airdrie might now be considered something of a commuter town.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In fact, housing construction in Airdrie has been very prominent in recent years, with builders developing a number of brownfield sites following the closure of various factories such as Boots (who closed their factory in 2004).
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Nonetheless, it does retain significant economic activity.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] There are two trading estates in the town, Brownsburn Industrial Estate and Osprey Trade Park.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Policing in Airdrie is undertaken by Police Scotland.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie is part of Coatbridge Area Command with Chief Inspector Kenny MacLeod as the Area Commander.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie also forms part of NA (or Monklands) sub division which includes Coatbridge and the surrounding area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] There is one police office in Airdrie and this is open 24 hours.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie Sheriff Court is a modern building in Graham Street which provides a comprehensive local court service for the area including civil actions and criminal cases.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] It is administered by the Scottish Court Service and part of the South Strathclyde, Dumfries and Galloway Sheriffdom headed by a Sheriff Principal.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] It replaced the old County Buildings in Bank Street which was demolished in 1969.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie railway station is on the electrified North Clyde Line.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This railway provides a frequent train service to Glasgow via Coatbridge Sunnyside and Easterhouse.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] In 2010, the Airdrie–Bathgate rail link re-opened providing Airdrie with a direct commuter train service to Bathgate, Livingston North and Edinburgh Waverley.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Drumgelloch railway station serves the eastern end of the town.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Including the satellite village of Caldercruix, Airdrie is served by four stations; Caldercruix, Drumgelloch, Airdrie, and Coatdyke, on the border of Airdrie and Coatbridge.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie has road links to Glasgow, Edinburgh, Livingston, Motherwell, and Cumbernauld and is situated close to the M8 motorway.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Bus services are largely undertaken by local operators, and links to Glasgow are provided by First Glasgow and McGills.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] McGill's took over most of the local companies in 2016 to form its 'Monklands' network in Go Zone 8.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] The services link all the local neighbourhoods with longer distance services e.g. the 212 from Coatbridge - Caldercruix via Airdrie and Plains, or the 247 from Monklands Hospital - Kirkintilloch via Airdrie, Glenmavis, Cumbernauld and Blackwood.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie is connected to the UK National Cycle Network by National Cycle Route 75.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] This route provides a path between Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] According to the Sustrans website: "there is currently a gap in the National Cycle Network route at Devol Glen, Port Glasgow." Other than the Sustrans path, there are no cycle lanes in Airdrie.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Airdrie is home to Monklands District General Hospital with a 24-hour Accident & Emergency department.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] Adjacent to Monklands Hospital is Maggie's Lanarkshire, part of the Maggie's Centres cancer support charity.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-north-lanarkshire] There is a community health centre in Airdrie city centre on Graham Street.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The seat has been held by Neil Gray of the Scottish National Party since the 2021 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The other eight constituencies of the Central Scotland and Lothians West region are Almond Valley, Bathgate, Coatbridge and Chryston, Cumbernauld and Kilsyth, Falkirk East and Linlithgow, Falkirk West, Motherwell and Wishaw, and Uddingston and Bellshill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The region covers all of the Falkirk council area, all of the North Lanarkshire council area, all of the West Lothian council area and part of the South Lanarkshire council area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] Prior to the 2025 boundary review Airdrie and Shots was one of nine constituencies forming the Central Scotland region.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The other eight seats in this region were: Coatbridge and Chryston, Cumbernauld and Kilsyth, East Kilbride, Falkirk East, Falkirk West, Hamilton, Larkhall and Stonehouse, Motherwell and Wishaw and Uddingston and Bellshill.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The region covered all of the Falkirk council area, all of the North Lanarkshire council area and part of the South Lanarkshire council area.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] Airdrie and Shotts was created at the same time as the Scottish Parliament, in 1999, with the name and boundaries of the existing Airdrie and Shotts constituency of the House of Commons.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] Ahead of the 2005 United Kingdom general election, Scottish constituencies for the House of Commons were mostly replaced with new constituencies, whilst initially being retained for elections to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] There is no longer any direct link between the boundaries used for the two parliaments.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] The seat was renamed simply *Airdrie* ahead of the 2026 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] It is now one of four Scottish Parliament constituencies covering the North Lanarkshire council area, the others being Coatbridge and Chryston, Cumbernauld and Kilsyth, Motherwell and Wishaw and Uddingston and Bellshill, the last of which spans parts of both North and South Lanarkshire.
[src:airdrie-north-lanarkshire/airdrie-scottish-parliament-constituency] Also standing for the Abolish the Scottish Parliament Party - regional votes are for the latter party only.
